			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I like this way of thinking about the the issue . . . in terms of functionality in context.
<br />

<br />
Like many others, my guild prefers off-tanking for crowd control.  The rationale for this:
<br />

<br />
1.  Off-tanking is simpler.  To use mez CC, the entire raid and the raid leader need to understand enchanter abilities.  One applicant with autoattack on can break the mez.  Training the raid force to work with enchanter CC is an annoyance to both raid leaders and players of other classes.
<br />

<br />
2.  Off-tanking is more efficient.  That paladin stunning the mob is also doing damage to it.  And others can lay dots and such on it without impeding the CC.  (Sigh our guild leader is a wizard and LOVES using AE damage spells and rains.)
<br />

<br />
3.  Off-tanking is more reliable.  No worries whether something is flagged immune, or too high level.  And not as much risk of the knight going splat and taking the cleric with him as when an enchanter gets a mez resist.
<br />

<br />
If off-tanking is not an option, the raid leader will try for out-of-camp CC and controlled pulls by a bard or a monk.
<br />

<br />
If that isn't feasible, the raid leader will opt to have rangers and bards kite the mobs.
<br />

<br />
Mez is the the last CC choice and used only when nothing else will work.
<br />

<br />
I agree that the posted "standard" is what is required to put enchanter CC back in place as a tactic sensible raid leaders would use.
<br />

<br />
In addition I think we need CC tools that are not mezzes.  I look at an old enchanter guide (it ends at level 50) and see that, back in the day, enchanters could stun, charm, root, kite, pacify and pet-tank for crowd control.  Most of these abilites are no longer viable in cutting edge content.  That needs to change.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
