<br />
I'm going to resist the urge to belittle this, and simply quote again.  From page 1, because I'm a lazy ass.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Laeyakk wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">How about I be concrete? 5 strait-out suggestions:
<br />

<br />
1&gt; Make new OOW charms different than old charms. New charms prevent haste from working. Mobs are flagged as being 'only new charmable' with seperate DI/DB tables. Charmed mob DI/DB is increased by the same amount you would otherwise have added to the built-in charm haste.
<br />

<br />
2&gt; Teach mobs to ignore buffs/gear while charmed. Make mobs you newly make charmed immune to haste and ignore gear (or refuse to accept gear) while charmed. Old creatures keep their properties. Charm DI/DB is scaled by the same amount you would otherwise have added to the built-in charm haste.
<br />

<br />
3&gt; See <a href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=enchanterbalance&amp;message.id=2898" target="_blank">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=enchanterbalance&amp;message.id=2898</a> -- Optimism.
<br />

<br />
To sum up:
<br />
Charm spell level caps are increased -- Beckon goes up to L 65, CoD to 67, and True Name to L 73. Charm becomes usable, theoretically, on any mob an enchanter encounters while XPing.
<br />

<br />
Charm gets built-in haste buffs that peak out at 100% at L 70. Charmed pets also automatically start dual-wielding. This makes most of the large charm-DPS increases automatic.
<br />

<br />
A L 73 mob, charmed, ends up doing about 350 DPS. Player melee is hitting 600 DPS on the same content.
<br />

<br />
Both mez and charm are coded to 'mitigate' past their level caps. Mez loses 20% duration, and charm loses 15% duration and DPS.
<br />

<br />
Enchanters gain impressive defensive abilities. Multiple fast-casting defence spells that work up to L 73, and the ability to mitigate damage like a tank (or a bit better) at a reasonably high mana cost (so enchanter-tanking can't be sustained).
<br />

<br />
(the details are probably clearer than this summary)
<br />

<br />
4&gt; Make charm spells have a pseudo-haste. This pseudo-haste only works on charmed mobs that use the new damage tables. Other mobs don't react to the effect - a matter of changing how creatures react to spells.
<br />

<br />
5&gt; A varient of &lt;2&gt;. Charm spells prevent buffs from working. Charm spells also have a lions-strength like spell effect that goes up with higher versions of the spell.
<br />

<br />
This means that a L 65 mob charmed with Compell does less damage than the same mob charmed with True Name. This has useful effects.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
